title: For Sale:  WWII M1 Garand
postcontent: Listed here is a very nice M1 Garand. The receiver S/N dates the gun to March 1944. It has a mix of WWII and post-WWII era parts, and they compliment each other to create a very nice shooting, and accurate, gun. Here are some highlights:Pros:- Has WRA bolt (-1 W.R.A.), which is very nice.- Has the earlier narrow-base gas cylinder with a ported gas plug. Has proper play on barrel splines, and the splines have not been peened.- Has an (unmarked) NM SA op rod (i.e. 77 op rod). Nearly new.- Has a brand new, properly finished CMP stock, and handguards, Beautiful!- Has a correct trigger housing (-12SA) and hammer (-5SA).- The gun is tight and cycles right!Cons:- Has an import-marked barrel (SA 10/53), from Blue Sky (Arlington, VA). More on this below. The muzzle wear is 5, but the bore rifling (lands and grooves) look pretty good. It shoots very good, and with reloads, I expect the barrel has a few thousand rounds of life left.- The trigger guard is milled (which is good) but the lockup pins are worn (more D-shaped than round). However, given the stock is new … this is good! The trigger group lockup is exactly as it should be and … as the wood naturally compresses … you can get a new trigger guard which will lockup tighter.About the Blue Sky Importer:M1 Garands were exported to US allies, and this gun was exported - most likely - to South Korea. Blue Sky (and others) reimported them. This creates some confusion, so to be clear: The gun is made with all USGI parts, with these notable exceptions: the stock is a CMP stock, and the gas plug is a ported, engineered part. I can substitute with a USGI ported plug, if desired (but, it won’t shoot as well).I am asking $800 firm for the gun. Here are a couple of “comparables” currently selling or sold on GB:609248865604489432
